reviews.text:
There used to be donuts here. In a hut. And it was one of the weirdest scenes in Santa Rosa.

Now there is coffee. Espresso, perfectly pulled. Baked goods. Even beer. And it is one of the calmest and friendly little spots in the entire downtown.

Is 3-5 times a week too many visits? Nah. Love this place. 

Areas for improvement: more chocolate chip cookies please (they seem to run out all the time).

I tried their Korean-style Brussel sprouts and they were great! I also had their lamb sandwich and was impressed. Their beer was delicious. The staff is very chill and friendly. I would recommend this place for good food, drinks, and vibes!
I'm yet to find a beer that I don't like on their rotation. Everything on the menu is fantastic, especially the house tacos!
Zagat rated for a reason. Great food, great beer, and the staff is perfect. best Cuban hands down I've ever had to date!

The tasting flight was an amazing deal! Our favorites were the 328 house ale and the pomegranate saison. Brussels were also bomb. Super friendly staff and cool decor. Will be spending more time here for sure.

It's about damn time winter hill got a place like this! 

Breakfast: The bagels are insanely delicious. I don't think I've ever had such a perfectly...

reviews.text: Great hidden gem. They brew their craft beers. I'm not a fan of beer, and they were good. The menu options were unique and delicious! They have a variety of events. The employees are nice. And everything is priced right. I'll definitely be going again.

Awesome beer, great food, and fantastic staff make this one of the places I will automatically recommend to anyone looking for a good local brewpub. It can get really crowded, but I've never felt as if the bartenders wanted to give me anything less than 100% of their attention, so huge props to the bar staff!

I give this place 3/5 because I believe in rounding up. The beer is fine, an excellent attempt for an ameteurs first try at a specific brew. Flavor profiles don't standout out as described, and no beers stand out against the classics I would love to see on tap at other bars. 

The atmosphere is causal, decor is tasteful but overall the vibe is obviously hipster. Be prepared to wait just shy of an hour for food and tables. 

If you're looking for another spot to add to your barcrawl Slumbrew isn't a bad spot to stop by. But if you're looking for a bar with character and exception, skip to the next suggested bar in better hopes.
Their beer is not only great but their menu pairs nicely. Try their BBQ nachos. You can feel your heart slowing down...in a good way.

Beer is great, environment is relaxed and wasn't overly crowded during the day or at night.  Plenty of board games and chill vibes.  Also had a late night comedy show, which wasn't really our thing, but still cool that it was offered on a Sunday night. Beer is fantastic. Will come back next time I am in Boston.
I made my first appearance at Slum Brew on a fine June Friday evening and have been back several times since. Upon entering, I was taken by the  ambiance...

beers.beerDescription: Flagraiser IPA is a big, hoppy tribute to the unfurling of the Grand Union flag atop Prospect Hill in Somerville, MA on January 1, 1776. This ale celebrates our passion for hop aroma and flavor balanced with just the right amount of malt. Huge aroma and resin-y flavors from the elusive Galaxy hops are the signature of this beer. Built on a solid base of pale malts, this double IPA makes generous use of hops from Columbus, Crystal and Galaxy with the Galaxy hops taking the lead during ten days of aggressive dry-hopping.

A refreshingly tart and crisp hefeweizen brewed with local MA wildflower honey, orange peel and coriander, and fermented with the juice from over 1,000 blood oranges. Itâs a cloudy, yet effervescent beer, with lingering banana and citrus notes balanced against a healthy wheat backbone and hoppy finish from Mt. Hood and Crystal hops.

Rich black porter with a unique blend of chocolate, coffee, roasted and nutty flavors. Brewed with cocoa powder and conditioned with cacao nibs from Taza Chocolate. Bold flavors from the cacao nibs and black malts are balanced with a special blend of pale malts, oats and wheat to produce a lush and lingering mouthfeel.

A smooth and alluring Belgian golden ale with complex fruity pineapple flavors set against a spicy finish. Dried jasmine flowers added in the boil work with a higher alcohol level to augment Belgian pilsen, caramel and honey malts. Hop character include Chinook and Moteuka hops grown in New Zealand.

An autumn brown ale with distinctive toasty flavors from an assortment of roasted malts and grains. As a seasonal, fall beer, its nutty characteristics offer a great companion to colder climate cuisine. A bright hop finish from Cascade and Fuggles balance the toasted grain notes to create a new expression of autumn brown ales.

It wasn't always his temperament, but they were the ones ... the ones that went looking for him after all. Today is a new day. Lobstah Killah Imperial Red Ale is a special blend of Maris Otter and other malts balance a resiny mix of Columbus, Cascade and Simcoe hops. Our hoppy imperial red ale is the beer of choice for imperial decisions.

LIMITED SEASONAL RELEASE! It's often said there is a better half responsible for making us whole, and so goes the inspiration for this ale. One half of the fermentation is cold lagered and the remaining half is finished as a warm ale fermentation. The result is a smooth and composed imperial cream ale well suited for contemplation.

How many hops are enough for an IPA? We think it's not just quantity, but the blend of varieties as we strive for hoppy delusions in this extremely limited release IPA for the lover of all things humulus lupulus. This beer is light golden in color from pilsner and caramel malts, with a cloudy haze from the addition of wheat. It's an unfiltered compilation of Nugget, Columbus, Zythos, Simcoe and a new experimental hop from the Pacific-Northwest referenced only by HBC-342.

Today, we breathe in deeply. Fresh air and the aromatic essence of Calypso, Ella and Pacific Jade hops fill the air and lighten our hearts while this golden ale lightens our mood. Today is an Island Day. Keep cold, enjoy now for today is the day. Serve at 45Âº - 50Âº F

You could gift this bottle as a reflection of your fine craft beer taste, drink it now to ease your holiday tension or cellar for the long winter ahead. For our first year of our Yankee Swap beer series, we selected rum barrels from our friends at Turkey Shore Distilleries and dark maple syrup from North Hadley Sugar Shack. This Strong Ale is a big beer with hints of maple and complex notes of oak and rum from the Old Ipswich rum barrels.
A LIMITED IPA project from Slumbrew Luma Luma is derived from a complex combination of malts, yeasts and hops so this multilayered IPA weighs in at 7.3% abv.
Gose with hibiscus

Summertime is for love, laughter and play, not envy. Never mind those luscious, long climbing vines of spicy, herbal hop cones over there. Sure there is a time for IPA, but today we will be content with smooth and floral Saison. Be happy. Brewed with Belgian aromatic malts, wheat and noble hops. Serve in a goblet or snifter at 45F for optimal enjoyment.

Hopheads go to great extremes in their lupulin quests. It's a worthy endeavor, but fraught with falling across the event horizon in a hoppy stupor. With swirling flavors from both dark malts and the crisp body from pilsner grains, our limited release black IPA will take you to the center of a hop explosion and back, without all the crushing gravity.

Meet Creep. Ever wonder who's responsible for seasonal beers popping up before their time? SeasonALE Creep thinks it's funny to release a pumpkin beer in August or a holiday ale in September. He's a greedy little character, robbing us of time and demanding we move on too soon. We'd be down on Creep, except he brought this refreshing Belgian-style saison brewed with light pilsner malts, wheat and galaxy hops.

Our white IPA is a hybrid ale brewed with wheat malts and fermented with fresh peach puree. The aromatic essence of peach flavors combines with a world of hoppy goodness from Galena, Amarillo and Citra hops.

This beer pours a deep red color with unique malty flavors from roasted barley, Munich, pilsen and caramel malts. A subtle hop spice is derived from German Perle and Hallertau hops.

SomervilleBrewingCompany.breweryDescription: Make good liquids, make good friends. Since its inception in 2011, the brewery has expanded distribution into six states, achieved annual production of over 2,000 barrels of beer and grown from 2 employees to over 35. The recent addition of two retail destinations to enjoy its core brand of Slumbrew beer with innovative food offerings, along with its own Somerville brewery location are milestones along an exciting path of growth. There are two locations in Somerville MA: The Brewery + Taproom at 15 Ward Street and an outdoor beer garden at Assembly Row.

userTips.tip: Great brews, friendly employees, Cartoon Network was on TV during our visit. Make your own flight - we picked 8 beers for ours.

reviews.text: John Harvard's is a Harvard square stand by with about average food and beer. Most of their beer they brew themselves is good but none of it has ever knocked my socks off. If I'm in Harvard sq I think this is a fun place to go but of course you have many options there
Nice collection of brew. Music can get a bit louder making talking a bit difficult

Nice tourist staple - we have returned on multiple occasions with various guests. Great place to stop by after a day of touring. They have an amazing lobster mac n' cheese -  a must try and good choice of beers.
Lively atmosphere. The food is very tasty too

Bad service. Had a $60 bill, paid it and noticed the next day that I was charged $116. When I called they said to take it up with the bank because they couldn't trace back my card information and there was nothing they could do to help me. I'll be sure to pay in cash next time.

reviews.text: Love this brewery! Not only do they have some great brews, recommend doing a few beer flights to discover your favorite, but the space is pretty awesome too. Two large rooms each with their own bar and a fireplace with couches that feels like you are in your own living room. Food truck out front also serves up some amazing food.

One of if not the best Brewery in the Boston area.  They have a huge selection of amazing beers, food trucks, and tons of events. Located in the "Fermentation District" of Everett, this is a wicked easy place to get to. 
If you are a total beer buff, they also offer a killer Barrel Society that you can buy into each year. Receiving member only releases. 
We frequent this place at least 3 or 4 times  month!

This place is amazing.  Was in Boston for a few days, and went to many breweries and tried many beers. This may have been my favorite.  Not really because of the beer (although the beer is fantastic and there is a wide selection), but more for the atmosphere and crowd.  Great vibes, huge space with plenty of room and plenty of people.  Met cool people, had a great night here. Highly recommended.
Enjoyed my first visit to the tap room. Tried some pretty good beer. Had a fun time with friends. The staff was helpful and friendly.

Night Shift is a destination in itself. A quick drive north of Boston, the facility is rather large with a host of parking. The dual taprooms make the space feel absolutely enormous. There is a wide variety of styles available, from their mainstay IPAs to their more adventurous sour and limited offerings. The outdoor space is also a nice option when the weather cooperates. Bringing food trucks on site also is a big plus. Draft pours can be split into samples/flights as well as full pours and growlers. You are also able to purchase bottles and cans for off site consumption. Night Shift is an absolute must hit for any craft beer enthusiast in the Boston area.
A fantastic brewery/tap room with excellent beers.  Lots of space, easy parking, passionate people.  Most of the food is from a rotating selection of Food...

userTips.tip: If you like beer, you'll LOVE Night Shift. The area is a little sketchy, but once you're inside, it's a beer lovers paradise. Try the Rose. Amazing.
Fantastic brewery with a constantly changing tap list of their own craft beers. Become a barrel society member you won't regret it.
They are totally cool with you bringing your own food. Bread and cheese goes great with beer!
The people who work here are awesome. Great place!

reviews.text: Inventive beers in a space that's a coffee shop during the day. Their sour beers are excellent. This place makes me love my neighborhood. The beers are a bit expensive, but there are growler fills if you want to save a bit of money.
Wonderful, very diverse selection of beers! Flights are a good value. Atmosphere is great! There seems to be a line on weekends and a good crowd on weekdays. Highly recommend!

My favorite coffee shop and my favorite bar. Go in the morning for coffee and lots of space to work, stay for an afternoon beer and then invite friends just before it gets crowded (usually around five or six) for a flight of tasty sour beers in the evening. There's really no need to leave :)

Great new Brewery with a good selection of different styles. They have fun and different activities most nights to keep things interesting. They also have a great coffee selection in an industrial and laid back setting.
Love the beer. Love the people. Great atmosphere. 6 stars!
The beer drinking scene does not get much more authentic than Lamplighter if you like a busy and hustling environment on the weekends! I am a brewer and...

An Amarillo and El Dorado hopped double IPA. Big hop candy and tropical fruit flavor and aroma.

A 100% Brettanomyces-fermented IPA.  Aroma of grilled pineapple, black pepper, and dank earth.  Complex and funky flavor from Brett byproducts and assertive hops.  Smooth and pithy grapefruit finish.
A wheat beer brewed with raw honey and chamomile flowers. Drinks easy with notes of honey, toast, and herbs.
A legislatively dank IPA bringing forward earthy hops, bright melon, and tropical fruit flavors.
100% Brettanomyces Fermented IPA. Classic Brett character mixed with fruity hops. Dry and effervescent.
A centennial dry-hopped Kettle Sour that pours a beautiful golden hue. Balanced subtle hop bitterness and tart acidity.
Classic and clean IPA brewed with citra, amarillo, and columbus hops. Hints of kiwi, melon, orange rind, and David Bowie.
Big Belgian Strong Ale brewed for the holiday season. Notes of chocolate covered cherries, plums, and nutmeg.
A bright and floral East Coast IPA with notes of strawberry and citrus leaf. Approachable, hazy and smooth with a balanced zesty orange bitterness. Bright and flavorful.
A Brettanomyces fermented Pale Ale aged in chardonnay barrels for 5 months. Dry and crisp, with hints of grape musk, pear, and a vanilla oaky-ness.
A 100% Brettanomyces fermented Pale Ale that balances tropical fruits with a wild funkiness.
Rotating DIPA series. A double IPA brewed with El Dorado hops. Hop candy, tropical and aromatic.
A true-to-style Belgian Blond Ale with distinct notes of clove, honeysuckle, and floral calendula.
An American IPA with balanced west and east coast flavors. Notes of pine and tropical fruit, and a full-bodied smooth mouthfeel.
A Holiday Belgian Strong Ale aged on cherries for 6 weeks. Malty, boozy, and a delectable cherry bomb!

LamplighterBrewing.name: Lamplighter Brewing Co.
LamplighterBrewing.breweryDescription: Our goal is to make beer that youâve never had anywhere else (or at least that you can't find very easily), but beer that is still drinkable and enjoyable. We want to use tradition as a launching point, and add complexity and depth with our choice of yeast and ingredients. Expect to see a lot of Brettanomyces fermentations, a lot of sour, a lot of funk, and a lot of fun. We hope when you see the name Lamplighter on a menu or label, youâll have a good idea that youâre in for something creative and delicious.

reviews.text: 'Soup Nazi' of the beer world.  Wait in line, get AGAINST the wall, MOVE IN, and wait for someone to say NEXT.  Yes, just like in Seinfeld, the product is good, but you better take it quickly and leave (no consumption allowed on the premises).
Get a growler and fill up with delicious beer. Sometimes a short line after work but they're good about moving your through and making recommendations.
Lines out the door for a reason - great selection and delicious brews.  My favorite local brewing company by far.
Excellent beer, but just remember you can't drink it here.
Didn't make it to the brewery, but had the pale ale with pizza down the street at Pastoral and it was awesome. Will try and pick up some to take home. Good stuff!
Trillium does one thing and it does it well. Don't come here expecting to chat up the brewer, get a tour or even have a pint. This location is about brewing...

beers.beerDescription: Our flagship American IPA highlights the distinctively aromatic Australian Galaxy hop.  The nose bursts with pine, citrus rind, melon and pineapple. Pronounced flavors of peach, clementine, and tropical fruits are accentuated with moderate bitterness and balanced by a light, biscuity malt character.

Our signature American pale ale balances light, crisp, malt character with an abundance of hop-derived aromatics and flavors from the use of Citra and Columbus. The fragrant nose is fresh citrus, tropical fruit, and peach. Bold flavors of pineapple and mango mix with dank notes of zesty citrus and fresh pine needles. With the smooth mouthfeel, gentle bitterness, and dry finish, Fort Point is our standard daily-drinker.

Brewed in celebration of the first anniversary of Row 34, our favorite Fort Point oyster bar and craft-beer purveyor, Vicinity highlights a neighborhood collaboration of passion and vision. Appearance is bright and straw-colored. Spicy, earthy aromas of tropical fruit notes abound. Complex flavors of grape juice, light citrus, and lychee emerge on the palate. The pilsner malt provides a cracker crisp malt character and clean, mineral finish.

In the spirit of tenacity and camaraderie, Mettle was first created to highlight the milestone of our inaugural year as a brewery. With an intense dual dry-hop treatment of Amarillo and Citra, this medium-bodied Double IPA beckons with aromatics of peach and nectarine. A fusion of grape juice and candied citrus greet the palate while accents of white-wine, grassy hop, and a mellow bitterness reveal themselves on a smooth, dry finish. We continue to brew Mettle in recognition of our devoted following of hopheads that have supported us from the very beginning.

This popular edition in our âStreetâ series of India Pale Ales spotlights the remarkably complex Mosaic hop. Melcher Street is hazy, pale orange in appearance and emits aromatic qualities of grapefruit, mild-earthy pine, and mango on the nose. Dank flavors of pine and green hop, along with juicy notes of tropical fruit, melon, and peach, are accentuated with crisp malt character, mild bitterness, and a soft, effervescent mouthfeel.

beers.beerName: Double Dry Hopped Fort Point Pale Ale
beers.beerDescription: This double dry hopped pale ale contains the same base ingredients, for both malt and hops, as Fort Point Pale Ale, but with an additional dry hop of Citra. The added hops richly enhance the juicy tropical fruit flavors of pineapple/mango, create elevated green, herbaceous aromatics, and increase body.

beers.beerName: Mosaic Dry Hopped Fort Point Pale Ale
beers.beerDescription: With this distinctively dank Fort Point variant we feature Mosaic in the dry hop. Pouring a faintly cloudy, canary gold, Mosaic Fort Point emits a fragrant nose of herbal-woodsy hop, passion fruit, and zesty meyer lemon. Thirst quenching flavors of juicy mango, peppy citrus, and earthy hop entwine on the palate with the familiar biscuity mouthfeel, medium body, and bone dry finish of our signature pale ale.

Our first IPA brewed and packaged at our new facility in Canton, MA.  El Dorado, Citra, and Columbus hops create a blast of citrus zest, pineapple, wet earth, and woody aromatics.  The flavor brings a pithy bitterness and just a touch of toasted malt.  Medium bodied with a dry, minerally finish.

Our Double Dry Hopped version of Melcher Street; this amped up American IPA features a heavy dose of Mosaic hops. The spicy, resinous, herbal aroma bursts with nuances of tart citrus, tangerine, clementine, and subtle green onion. Bold flavors of under-ripe melon, cantaloupe rind, and pineapple are highlighted with gentle bitterness and delicate, biscuity malt character.

Same base grist as Sleeper Street IPA, but with a double dose of El Dorado in the dry hop. These El Dorado hops impart a powerful aroma of distinctive lime zest, along with notes of grapefruit juice, and a subtle woodsy earthiness.  The taste is bright, floral, and citrusy hop upfront and finishes with candied lime. As with all Trillium âStreetâ IPAâs, Double Dry Hopped Sleeper Street is dry with medium-light body and a crisp finish.

Pot and Kettle with Cold Brew is just one of our many inspired collaborations with Barrington Coffee Roasting Company. With decades of experience hand-selecting and roasting single origin beans from across the world, cold brewed Barrington coffees provide the perfect addition to our signature oatmeal porter. Like a fresh pull of espresso, Coffee Pot & Kettle pours a dark, almost black color with a dense, sepia brown head. Aromas of fresh brewed coffee, nutty cocoa, dark fruits, burnt-caramel, and subtle vanilla waft out of the glass. Moderate in body with medium carbonation; Deep, roasty flavors of cacao, earthy-coffee, mocha, toffee, and dark malt sweep over the palate with an oatmeal-based creaminess and gentle bitterness. To fully explore the wide range of unique aromas and flavors derived from the diverse array of coffees available, we continuously experiment with varying Barrington roasts and blends with each batch of Pot & Kettle with Cold Brew.

UPPER CASE has a delicate, dry pilsner malt character with a smooth, soft, doughy mouthfeel from the raw wheat, oily hop resin which all serves as a canvas for this twice dry hopped 9% double IPA. Overipe mango, pineapple and passion fruit aromas leap out as the beer is poured. The impression of tropical fruit also takes the lead in the flavor which is layered further by white wine, pine resin and grapefruit zest. Hopped primarily with Mosaic with supporting roles played by Galaxy, Citra and Columbus.

Following in the footsteps of our other âStreetâ IPAâs, Sleeper shares the same base grains while placing the unique El Dorado hop at center stage. Opaque orange-yellow in color with floral aromas of lime zest, grapefruit peel, pine sap, and candied orange. Juicy, hop-driven flavors of bright citrus, melon, and herbal pine are balanced with medium bitterness, fluffy mouthfeel, and dry finish.

beers.beerName: Double Dry Hopped Congress Street IPA
beers.beerDescription: This amplified version of Congress Street IPA is a focused exhibition of the Galaxy Hop. Milky and yellow-orange in appearance, Double Dry Hopped Congress Street emits fragrant aromatics of mango, pine resin, grapefruit, pineapple, and peach. Explosive flavors of tropical fruit, grassy hop, nectarine, orange rind, and creamy malt inundate the palate with a thick, rich mouthfeel and soft, effervescent carbonation. The finish is full and oily, yet clean, with a light, modest bitterness.

The first Double IPA produced at our Canton brewery. Featuring four powerful aromatic hop varieties, Galaxy, Mosaic, Nelson Sauvin, and Columbus, Scaled Up emits dank, spicy, aromas that lead into fruity, citrusy flavors of peach and orange on the palate. Lighter in body than most of our other Double IPAs, Scaled Up finishes dry and smooth with a pleasant bitterness.

In another exciting collaborative effort with our neighbors at Barrington Coffee Roasters, we bring you a bold American stout infused with cold-brewed coffee. PM Dawn exhibits an earthy, freshly roasted coffee bean and dark chocolate/mocha nose. The flavor profile consists of vanilla, hot chocolate, and caramel along with rich espresso. With a medium to heavy body, luscious mouthfeel, and light bitterness, PM Dawn is balanced and full, smooth with a drying roast character.

Our enhanced version of Summer St. IPA features a secondary dry hopping with Simcoe which leads to a fuller mouthfeel, amplified nose, and an intensified depth of grassy, raw hop character. Double Dry Hopped Summer Street is hazy, sunflower gold in appearance with strong aromatics of pine and lemon. Bold flavors of juicy tangerine, pine resin, and green pear dominate the palate with modest bitterness and a dry finish.

Brewed with 30% wheat, this hoppy, golden American ale features Galaxy and Citra in the dry hop. Bright aromatics of overripe peach, orange rind, and green, herbal hops flood the nose while balanced flavors of tropical fruit, citrus, and creamy wheat excite the palate. Refreshingly light bodied with a soft, fluffy mouthfeel, Pier finishes dry with a slightly mineral bitterness.

Brewed to test the Mettle of our loyal hopheads, this dank, full-bodied double IPA features intense dual additions of Amarillo and Galaxy. Bright aromatics of peach and nectarine fuse with flavors of tropical fruit and grapefruit on the palate. Accents of pine, resinous hop, and a clean bitterness reveal themselves on a smooth, dry finish.

As we prepare to open our new facility in Canton, MA, we release our debut brew: Launch Beer. This special brew signifies a collective milestone for the entire Trillium team. Bright in appearance and light in body, this refreshing pale ale bursts with floral hop aromatics of honeysuckle and passion fruit. Featuring Mosaic/Citra in the dry hop and a crisp Pilsner malt backbone, Launch Beer exhibits graceful flavors of stone fruit and citrus with a satisfyingly sessionable bitterness. We raise a glass to you; the devoted community of supporters who have helped us make our dream a reality!

Same distinctive grain bill as the other "Street" IPA's, but heavily dry hopped with Simcoe. Our treatment of Simcoe results in beautifully balanced aromatics and provides a satisfying depth of hop-driven flavor. Summer Street IPA bursts with scents of spicy pine, lemon, and grape juice while focused flavors of citrus, pear, and essence of pine wash over the palate. Finish is dry with moderate, resinous bitterness.

Secret Stairs is our signature Boston Stout. Bold and balanced; satisfying with a substantial body, but not syrupy or sweet. Roasted malt provides a nutty, earthy backdrop to bitter cocoa and little hints of caramel. Smooth mouthfeel with a drying sensation on the finish. We brew Secret Stairs to highlight the unique physical connection between Summer Street and A Street. We raise a pint of Secret Stairs to The Fort Pointer; the neighborhood's favorite protagonist!
3rd Anniversary beer. Double IPA brewed with Sauvignon Blanc grape juice.

Brewed in appreciation of The Publick House, a craft beer mecca in Brookline, MA where close friends and warm hospitality welcome us time after time. The Publick House IPA features Citra, Centennial, and Columbus hops with an aroma bursting with fresh orange juice and under-ripe peach along with notes of toasted malt. The flavor profile is more bitter than our âStreetâ IPAs, but with a toasted, bready malt character to balance. Bitter grapefruit flavors emerge with mild pine on the finish.

The simplicity of Trilliumâs grist of barley and wheat delivers a wonderfully complex yet still approachable beer. The house blend of farmhouse yeasts and Columbus and US Goldings hops drive a distinctive character in this rustic, unfiltered ale. A beautiful nose of spice and pepper, coupled with flavors of fermentation-derived fruit and more pepper. Firm bitterness, nicely carbonated with a dry finish, but thereâs also a wonderful smoothness in the mouthfeel from the wheat.

TrilliumBrewingCompany.name: Trillium Brewing Company
TrilliumBrewingCompany.breweryDescription: We are a family owned and operated brewery in the Fort Point Channel neighborhood of Boston, Massachusetts. We created Trillium to realize our dream of bringing creative and flavorful beers to you. These beers are what we envision might have been made today, if a centuries old beer culture had naturally evolved in New England.  To achieve this vision, we stand our craft beers on the shoulders of native ingredients and artisan practices, balancing them with modern-day expertise.

userTips.tip: The 1st brewery to open in Boston proper in decades, Trillium was named 1 of RateBeer's top 10 new breweries for 2013. Tastes, growlers & releases at the taproom; bottles on CBC shelves regularly!

reviews.text: Great place to check out when in Boston. Awesome beer selection and the pretzels with dipping sauce are amazing, and that's coming from someone who is not big into pretzels. They offer many different beer flights so you can sample many different beers before you commit. Downsides are that there is almost always a long wait to get in on the weekends and that it is very crowded once inside, but they can't really help that other than expanding. Overall would recommend you check this place out, even if you are not a huge beer drinker.

Nice, fun place. Good selection of beer, and the pretzels were very good.

Tour was also a lot of fun. The two tour guides did a great job. Very informative and very entertaining.
Great experience. I am not a big beer drinker but still enjoyed the place. Their seasonal flavors are worth the regular detour to the South End.
Love the short batch beer choices at the brew hall. Always something new to pick. Terrific annual holiday parties and festivals.
I'm not a beer drinker, but enjoyed this place. The tour is $5, and it comes with several tastings. I liked the cider, so it worked out. The pretzels at the main bar are amazing!!

This was my favorite brewery that I visited on my last trip to Boston.
The bar area was massive in size with plenty of space with everyone to enjoy a beer...

beers.beerDescription:
We started brewing this beer as a summer seasonal in 1993.  There were some great IPAs out in the Pacific Northwest, but no local IPAs on the east coast.  We wanted to have a local IPA, so we brewed one.  People absolutely loved it, and so did we.  So we made it a year-round beer, and itâs now our bestselling beer and our flagship.
Description: Since its introduction, Harpoon IPA has remained unique in its ability to balance hop bitterness with a strong malt backbone. Dry-hopped with Cascade hops, it has a floral hop aroma and a finish that is bitter (it is an IPA after all!) without being harsh or astringent. Combined with a malty sweetness and the fruity esters of our proprietary yeast, those hops create a beer that is wonderfully hoppy but clean and refreshing enough to enjoy a few of - and we hope you do.

Light, crisp, refreshing UFO White follows in the tradition of spiced wheat beers that have been brewed in Belgium for well over 300 years. Brewed with orange peel and coriander, UFO White is the perfect choice for a summerâs barbecue, a night out with friends or any time you're thirsting for something a little different. Like all UFO beers, we leave UFO White UnFiltered.

Itâs a simple story; we brew this beer because we like pumpkin (pumpkin pie, really) and thought an unfiltered pumpkin ale would be great, especially during the New England fall.  Turns out it is. Imagine a pumpkin vine wound its way in a field of barley, and a brewer harvested it all to make a beer. Add Northwestern hops and a blend of spices, and you've got UFO Pumpkin. The malt combination provides a smooth body and slightly sweet flavor, which balances perfectly with the earthy notes derived from the pure pumpkin. And like all of our UFO beers, UFO Pumpkin is UnFiltered.

Winter Warmer was Harpoon's first seasonal beer. It was designed to be enjoyed during the holiday season. Note the aroma of cinnamon. There is no aromatic hop added that might overpower the distinct spice scent. A smooth, medium bodied ale spiced with cinnamon and nutmeg.

When we first started thinking of a UFO summer seasonal, 
we knew we had our work cut out for us. We loaded up the 
vans for the beach and spent days âresearchingâ every 
combination of fresh fruit juice and beer we could think of 
until we discovered a combination that made our decision 
easy. Sweet with a hint of tartness, UFO Big Squeeze Shandy 
is perfect for all your summer adventures.
A beer brewed to be enjoyed with summertime activities.  It is light, refreshing, and crisp.

Harpoon Octoberfest is a malty tribute to fall, balanced by a gentle hop bitterness.  In keeping with tradition, it is a Marzen-style beer, brewed with abundant quantities of Munich, Chocolate, and Pale malts. Those malts provide a solid, full body and create the beerâs deep color.  It is a rich, flavorful beer.

This mango-infused Pale Ale begins with a subtle tropical aroma of passion fruit and mango. Golden-copper in color, it has a light body, slight hop bitterness, and malty sweetness, and finishes with a kiss of mango.
The Long Thaw White IPA style blends the spiciness of a Belgian Wit and the American hop character of an IPA.

Harpoon Leviathan Imperial IPA will challenge your senses and your palate. As the vibrant aroma rushes out of your glass you will notice the blend of piney and tropical fruit notes.  At first sip, this big beer starts with apowerful hop bitterness up front and an aggressive hop flavor and character throughout. 

Leviathan Imperial IPA is brewed with tons of pale malt and just enough caramel malt to provide a sweet malt body to balance the hop intensity. We used copious amounts of a variety of hops including Chinook, Centennial, Simcoe, and Amarillo at various points during the boil to create a complex hop flavor and clean lingering bitter finish. We then fermented the beer with HarpoonÃ¢â¬â¢s own versatile proprietary yeast.   Finally, we dry hopped at a rate of over 1 lb a barrel to produce this beerÃ¢â¬â¢s massive aroma.

We have added natural raspberry flavor to our UFO Hefeweizen to create this beer.  Consistent with the hefeweizen style, this beer is unfiltered and cloudy with a solid foamy head.  UFO Raspberry has a distinctive, hazy rose color.  The scent of fresh raspberries hits the nose immediately, along with a subtle bready aroma from the wheat and yeast.  The body is light and the unfiltered yeast provides a soft mouthfeel.  The taste of the fruit compliments the beer nicely, neither overwhelms the other.  There is a faint sweetness on the palate, which finishes cleanly in a semi-dry, tart finish.

In 2011 Harpoon co-founders Rich Doyle and Dan Kenary brewed a Rye IPA as part of the breweryâs 100 Barrel Series. It quickly became a favorite at the brewery, so we decided to make it year-round. 

This beer is brewed with our proprietary yeast â the same yeast weâve used since first brewing Harpoon Ale â and some interesting hop varieties. The combination of Pale, Rye, Caramel 60, Flaked Rye, and Vienna yield a complex malt body that stands up to the spiciness of the rye and the pronounced hop flavor. The rye also adds a reddish hue to the beer. The kettle additions of Centennial, Apollo, and Chinook, and the dry hop addition of Falconerâs Flight add a multidimensional hop character.

Harpoon Take 5 was first brewed on the Breweryâs 10-barrel system in early 2014. With each pilot batch the recipe was tweaked until the desired balance between hop aroma and malt character was achieved. This final version begins with a vibrant citrus and pine hop aroma from Simcoe and Amarillo hops and follows through with a sturdy malt profile from the combination of Pale, Vienna, Carapils, and English Amber malts. Hop forward but not too bitter, low ABV but with a significant malt body â a truly sessionable beer.

The unfiltered yeast remains in suspension, giving this style its signature cloudy color and a soft mouthfeel.  Unlike traditional Bavarian hefeweizens, however, UFO Hefeweizen uses a northern German ale yeast to produce it's signature "citrus-like" aroma.

Inspired by the classic tale. Cinnamon, clove, and ginger 
combine with an unfiltered wheat beer in this deliciously 
spiced, gingerbread-inspired beer.

Our head brewer at our Windsor brewery homebrewed a batch of chocolate stout for himself after trying the style at a beer dinner and loving it.  After several Harpooners tried Scottâs batch, we knew that we needed to add this beer to our lineup. It was originally introduced as a limited edition extra in our winter mix pack back in 2008, but it was soon apparent that our drinkers wanted more of this beer (a beer made with chocolateâ¦not too hard to understand!), so we brought it back in 6-packs in 2010.

A chocolate stout is a beer with a noticeable dark chocolate flavor. This flavor is created from the use of darker, more aromatic malt that has been roasted or kilned until it acquires a chocolate color. Harpoon Chocolate Stout is brewed with an abundance of chocolate malt and a touch of chocolate.

This Hoppy Amber Ale is our tribute to the quintessential season of change. A bright hop aroma from late hop additions plays with its strong malt backbone. Amber hued, medium bodied, with hints of citrus and pine, this ale is made for the crisp days (and nights) of fall.

Harpoon Cider is crafted from only one ingredient: freshly pressed apples. We ferment it with our house yeast, yielding a clean but refreshing all natural cider. 
Harpoon Cider is also naturally gluten-free. Its gluten content has been independently measured at less than 20 parts per million, meeting the FDA's proposed threshold for gluten-free.

Having brewed in South Boston since 1987, it was probably only a matter of time before we decided to commemorate St. Patrickâs Day (Evacuation Day - coincidentally a holiday - in Boston).  Itâs a beer that we thought would pair well with the late winter as well: malty enough to stand up to the cold but balanced enough to hint at Spring. 

Harpoon Celtic Ale features a deep ruby color, medium body, and a balanced malt bill created by Irish Ale malt and a touch of roasted barley. Rich in tradition and sessionable in character, Harpoon Celtic is the ideal Spring seasonal.
Golden and refreshing, flavorful but smooth, with a crisp, dry finish. A balancing act of the finest ingredients for a refreshing new breed of craft beer.
This draft-only Irish stout was made with six different types of malt, including roasted and chocolate, with a small dose of Willamette hops.
A Double IPA that's slightly sweet with a lingering bitterness.

Locally harvested pumpkins and apples are combined with seasonal spices to craft this pure and natural craft cider.
Harpoon Pumpkin Cider is also naturally gluten-free. Its gluten content has been independently measured at less than 20 parts per million, meeting the FDA's proposed threshold for gluten-free.

Last fall our brewers were improvising a new beer in our 10-barrel kettle. We had some fresh pumpkin puree leftover from a recent brew of our UFO Pumpkin, so the brewers threw that in the kettle with a bit of molasses, cinnamon, nutmeg, and some roasted malts. It turned out to be delicious, so we thought weâd share it with everyone. Half imperial stout, half pumpkin ale, with aromas of dried fruit, chocolate, and freshly baked pumpkin pie, this black full-bodied stout is ready to be enjoyed now or saved for a chilly fall evening.

HarpoonBrewery.name: Harpoon Brewery
HarpoonBrewery.breweryDescription: Love Beer. Love Life. Employee-Owned, brewed in Boston, MA and Windsor, VT.

This little brewery is now served all over the country and has 2 breweries (one here and on in Windsor, VT). Take the tour and enjoy some free samples!
The hour long tasting is the BEST!

FREE tastings every weekday from 2-4pm and weekend tours most of the day for just $5. Boston Beer - the best around.
Go to a beer tasting and reward yourself by tasting the fine beer!

BEST SAM ADAMS I HAVE EVER HAD!!!
The brewery is not very large but it was informative and fun. The tour guides were cool and the best part is your get to partake in some of the finest beverage ever created by man.... BEER

Funny, short and informative tour of the Sam Adams brewery.  This is where they invent their new flavors, not where they actually produce the beer for major distribution. Definitely worth a stop - if not for the free tour then for the free beer ;)
Jeff was in the majority of our tour and great... it's free and you get beer so not sure how to give this less than 5 stars. Only hour and informative enough to not put you to sleep
Free tour with awesome guides. The tour will show you around the place and give you some samples of yeast and other ingredients used in making the beer....

beers.beerDescription: Samuel Adams Boston LagerÂ® is the best example of the fundamental characteristics of a great beer, offering a full, rich flavor that is both balanced and complex. It is brewed using a decoration mash, a time consuming, traditional four vessel brewing process discarded by many contemporary brewers. This process brings forth a rich sweetness from the malt that makes it well worth the effort. Samuel Adams Boston LagerÂ® also uses only the finest of ingredients including two row barley, as well as German Noble aroma hops. The exclusive use of two row barley not only imparts a full, smooth body but also gives the beer a wide spectrum of malt flavor ranging from slightly sweet to caramel to slightly roasted. The Noble hops varieties, Hallertau Mittelfruh and Tettnang Tettnanger, add a wide range of floral, piney and citrus notes, which are present from the aroma, through the flavor, to the lingering smooth finish. We take great pride in the Noble hops used in our beers. They are hand selected by Jim Koch and our other brewers from the world's oldest hops growing area. Among the world's most expensive, they cost twenty times as much as other hops.

In 1810, the Oktoberfest tradition was born when Munich celebrated the Crown Princeâs wedding with a special beer and 16 day party. Our version of this classic style blends rich malts for a hearty, smooth flavor with notes of caramel creating a brew thatâs perfect for the season, or whatever youâre celebrating.

Samuel AdamsÂ® Summer Ale is an American wheat ale. This hazy golden unfiltered brew combines crisp wheat with the bright citrus of lemon peel and the subtle spice of Grains of Paradise.  This rare African pepper, closely related to cardamom, was first used as a brewing spice in the 13th Century and adds just the right peppery kick. All of these flavors come together to create a thirst quenching and utterly refreshing brew perfect for those warm summer days.

Bold and rich, with a touch of holiday spice
The first thing one notices in a Samuel AdamsÂ® Winter Lager is its color: the deep brown of winter. Then comes the magical aroma which promises something special on the tongue. The warm aroma of cinnamon and ginger which blends with the toasty sweetness of the malted barley and hint of citrus.
A White Ale brewed with a blend of fresh ground spring spices including orange, plum, and fresh ground coriander.

Perfect for any summer day, Samuel AdamsÂ® Porch Rocker was inspired by traditional Bavarian Radlers that mix beer with German-style lemonade.  For our bright and citrusy Radler, we blended a Helles beer with lemon for a fresh-squeezed lemon taste, effervescent sweetness, and slightly tart, refreshing finish.Â  A light malt character and hint of hops balance out this summer brew.

As crisp as the first snowfall of the year, this unfiltered white ale is blended with holiday spices including cinnamon, nutmeg, and orange peel.  The familiar citrus and wheat characters of the ale are complemented by the warmth of the spices for a festive brew thatâs perfect for the season.

Ale brewed with Cherries, crisp and fruity with a hint of honey.  Samuel Adams Cherry WheatÂ® follows the centuries old American tradition of brewing beer with native ingredients, in this case Michigan cherries as well as a touch of honey. The sweet fruitiness of the cherries is balanced against the crisp, cereal note from the malted wheat and the subtle citrus flavor from the Noble hops. The end result is a sweet, refreshing beer that is light on the palate but long on complexity.

Spicy and Bold, a big Christmas cookie of a beer.
Samuel AdamsÂ® Old FezziwigÂ® Ale is the Christmas cookie of beer. Bursting with spices of the season and a remarkably full body, it helps those long winter nights pass much quicker. The full body hits the palate first with a depth of malt character ranging from sweeter toffee and caramel notes to the more dark, roasty chocolate notes. Then come the spices in full force. Cinnamon, ginger and orange peel dance on the tongue bringing with them the celebratory spirit that goes hand in hand with the season.
This double IPA is big, brewed with over 5 lbs per barrel of American and Australian hops, and packed with fruity, citrus, pine, and resin notes for a bold hop finish. Cheers!

Brewed with real grapefruit for an added punch of citrusy goodness that amplifies the tropical fruit and citrus notes from the hops.Â  A hint of juiciness rounds out the bitterness and brings a refreshing finish to this bold, bright, thirst-quenching IPA.Â

A unique brew that combinines the intense hop character of an IPA with the crisp spicy wheat character of a Belgian-style white ale. The white ale and IPA combination make this crisp, smooth, yet hop-friendly beer the perfect pairing with a variety of meats and cheeses. Brewed with apricots and spices.

This dark beer has a big, malty character with the added sweetness of chocolate. Chocolate Bock is slowly aged on a bed of rare dark cocoa nibs, the primary ingredient in chocolate. Known for their quality, these cocoa nibs harvested in Ecuador, impart complex aromas and flavors from chocolaty to fruity, nutty, earthy, and citrusy.

A crisp, refreshing version of a traditional Belgian beer. Fruity, slightly spicy flavors from the Belgian yeast are balanced by toffee and caramel notes from our blend of malts. The hops provide a citrus character that rounds out this enjoyable brew.
Our take on the classic hybrid style from Cologne Germany, Escape Route combines the subtle fruit notes of an ale with the smooth crispness of a lager for a bright, refreshing brew.

Samuel Adams Noble Pils is one of the only brews made with all five Noble hops from the worldÃ¢â¬â¢s growing regions. its bright flavor and lively, citrus hop character reminds us that the warm days of spring are just a few weeks away.

beers.beerName: Samuel Adams Merry Maker Gingerbread Stout
beers.beerDescription: Gingerbread stout brewed with cinnamon, cloves, nutmeg, and ginger as well as well as East Kent Goldings & Fuggles hops
The distinct hop character of an IPA in a smooth lager.  The hops in this brew lend a bright grapefruit, citrus, floral aroma and flavor with a refreshing, crisp lager finish.
Four types of West Coast hops add bold notes of pine and juicy grapefruit to this deep golden wheat ale, for a crisp flavor thatâs a refreshing escape from winterâs lingering chill.

Malty and slightly sweet, balanced by earthy notes from the hops.  The gentle rain and fertile soil of Ireland helped inspire this style of ale, known for being remarkably balanced. Pale and Caramel malts give the beer its rich, deep red color and distinctive caramel flavor. The sweetness of the malt is pleasantly balanced by a pronounced hop bitterness and an earthy note from the East Kent Goldings hops. Samuel AdamsÂ® Irish Red finishes smooth and leaves you wanting to take another sip.

Amber, smooth, and resinous, this ale was inspired by our exploration of Australian hops.  We discovered that their rugged, spicy and piney character brightened a back-bone of roasted caramel malts, creating a beer with surprising depth and smoothness.

WHITE CAPPED AND LIVELY â the frothy white head of this distinctive nitro brew softly cascades into bright gold.   The first sip reveals a smooth velvety taste with a light wheat character and hints of orange while an undercurrent of peppery spice adds a bright finish.

A laidback golden pilsner thatâs full of character.  The fun of brewing is that itâs always evolving, even in the worldâs most popular beer style, the pilsner, thereâs still room for creativity.  For our German Pilsner we wanted to showcase both new & heritage hops from the original hop gardens of Bavaria.  The classic Noble hops offer a floral spiciness while the new varieties create a fruity & citrusy character for an elegant, light bodied yet flavorful brew.
A fresh take on a traditional Belgian-style white ale, brewed with orange & tangerine peel, coriander, & grains of paradise for a crisp, citrusy brew with a hint of spice.
Blueberry Hill Lager is a blueberry kellerbier style beer. Look for it exclusively in the Beer of Summer variety pack (2013) and on draft for special events.

SamuelAdamsBrewery.name: Boston Beer Company
SamuelAdamsBrewery.breweryDescription:
Jim Koch founded the Boston Beer Company back in 1984 after brewing the first batch of Samuel Adams Boston Lager in his kitchen. It was his mission to reshape the way American beer drinkers thought of American beer. 

Just six weeks after introducing Samuel Adams Boston Lager to the public, it brought home the "Best Beer in America" honors at the Great American Beer Festival in Denver. An honor it went on to win 3 more times before that particular award was discontinued.

Today, Samuel Adams makes more than 21 styles of award winning beer and is recognized around the globe as a hot house of new beer ideas.

If you share our passion, join us here as a fan! 

Cheers!

The Boston Beer Company, Boston MA

Free tours and tastings at the brewery between 10 a.m. and 3 p.m. Mon. - Thurs., plus Saturdays (the tours leave every 45 minutes or so). On Fridays, tours continue through 5:30 p.m.
Take a fun and informative tour through the Samuel Adams Brewery. Plus free beer is part of the tour.

Go on a brewery tour to learn all about the beer making process. Oh, and to sample!

beers.beerDescription: A not very bitter beer at all, the ESB has a smooth, malty initial mouthful that transitions to a marmalade like fruitiness from the East Kent Goldings hop variety. Toffee and light dried fruit notes.
Solid malt with hard candy sweetness. Big grapefruit notes, hints of lime and tropics from Citra kettle and dry hopping. Tightly wound with dark super fruit character from our Belgian yeast.
Piney, resinous & brilliant.  Moderate bitterness from this brownish red IPA is perfect for post-summer porch sitting.

Dark brown with Chestnut highlights. Roasted coffee and chocolate aroma. Super smooth, complex palate from de-bittered dark malts, German hops, and our house lager yeast. Berliner Weisse, the âpeopleâs champagneâ. Tart and crisp.  Highly effervescent with sparkling wine notes and a crackery malt finish. Try with raspberry or woodruff syrup for a fun addition.
Fully bright and deep golden fall classic. Brewed with Vienna and Pilsner malts with a malty sweetness.

A Brown Porter aged on Cocoa Nibs. Sweet chocolate syrup aroma with roast coffee notes. Fairly light bodied, with a rich, lingering finish of semi-sweet chocolate and roasted malt flavors. ABV: 5.3% B_ Su_e _o dri_k y_ur O_a_tin_!

Perfect golden straw color, our version of the Pilsner
is bursting with grassy herbal notes from Noble

Our Savin Summer Stout, but fermented with American Ale yeast & a healthy dose of Chinook hops, lending pine & fruit notes to this dry roasty classic.

DorchesterBrewingCompany.name: Dorchester Brewing Co.
DorchesterBrewingCompany.breweryDescription:
Dorchester Brewing Company is a partner brewing facility in Dorchester, MA, right in the heart of Boston. When you visit our brewery, youâll enjoy more than your typical tasting room. Our 20 line tap system is filled with a wide variety of fresh craft beer including our house beers, local brewing partners and regional collaborators on tap for all to consume and taste. beers.beerDescription: White Ale with Key Lime juice

There's not much new to say about IPAs since there are five thousand or so other commercial examples out there, but it is a style that's a personal favorite of ours - we tend to prefer hops with the big, fruity, juicy flavors that are all the rage with the young'uns these days. But since this is our mainstay year-round IPA (don't worry, hopheads, we'll have plenty more variations on the style once we're rolling) we've tried to balance that out a bit (for everyday drinkin' we tend to prefer something that doesn't necessarily smell like a fruit salad with perfume on it) with some malty goodness and a dab or two of some slightly-more-nuanced hop varieties (don't get me wrong, we're all about intense flavor. But you wouldn't want an all-syrup Squishee every day, would you?). Needless to say, this is one you'll miss in between pours.

I used to work with a girl named Kelly who didnât like dark beers until she drank my porter. Then every time I mentioned brewing within twenty feet of her, sheâd ask, âAre you brewing your porter?â and then sheâd start telling the same story I just told you, only ten thousand times longer. Eventually, I brewed the porter again in the hopes of getting her to shut up about it. It didnât work, but the beer was a keeper.

Since we like a taste of home in our beers, we set our sights on the fabled Unicorn of American Brewing: a beer that's light (in color/body/etc.) that won't let you down in the flavor department. And lo, we done it! We took a cream ale and goosed it with some good ol' Bone Up magic, and made a tasty brew that'll disappear from your glass before you know it and then you'll have to try and convince your roommate to get you more so you don't have to get up. Iâm told that the British call that âmoreishness.â There, you learned something today. Go ahead and crack one open, you earned it.

In keeping with our commitment towards not dumping a bunch of weird goop in our beers, this inky black stout's made with real-ass orange peel and a whole lotta Taza cocoa nibs. Itâs a surprisingly smooth sip of suds that gives you a good warm tingle in your belly.

Sometimes you just gotta have an old-school citrus-and-pine IPA, so we took some Classic American Hops and chucked them in the kettle with some Cascade from our friends down the road and mixed in just a *pinch* of Bone Up Magic. We ain't gonna strip the enamel off your teeth, but we are gonna give you a solid beer for solid times. Enjoy.
Light bodied, citrusy dark beer brewed with witbier spices
Dark Mild

This jaunty little wheat ale is packed full o' hops and just burstin' with floral notes and whiffs of tropical fruit. This beer is just beggin' to be quaffed as you make the most of these last summer days!

Brewed to pair with the music of the Original Gravity Concert Series, this playful lil' farmhouse ale is ready to take your tastebuds for a spin with the zip of fresh ginger, lemony hops, and the peppery spiciness of rye!

This mutt of a beer is the bastard child of a saison, a double IPA, and a tripel - born by accident and kept by happy coincidence. It has the hoppiness of an IPA, the spicy pepperiness of a tripel, and a fistful of rye. It's a sensorial thrill ride, and we don't think you'll be disappointed.

After we used Blue Ox malt for Bullhead, we were a bit smitten so we ordered a whole bunch more without really having any plan on what to make with it. Then one day, inspiration struck in the form of a terrible pun, and a plan was hatched. Similar(ish) in spirit to Bullhead, this beer is made to showcase the quality/qualities of Blue Ox malt, heavily featuring their "Vye-Enna" malt to make a light 'n' fruity BDG. Enjoy!

This is the second entry in our loosely-defined series of single-hop beers made with hops that nobody cares about. This time around we're focusing on Cluster - an old-school American hop that combines lemony citrus character (in times of shortage, it's used as a substitute for Cascade) with a bit of Wild American earthiness. It's a cool lil' hop, and we're showcasing it by using it in a a solid caramel-forward pale ale base that leans a ways toward the red end of the color spectrum.

Since we can't get enough of that Blue Ox Malt goodness, we figured we'd test its mettle when paired with fistful after fistful of punchy, fruity hops - the end result is a beer well suited for any weekend activity, whether you're at the discotheque or simply going for restaurant.

As this is our fiftieth batch, we wanted to do something with a nod towards our first-ever batch, only bigger and better. So we gathered up a figurative ton of Empire Malt, a moderately huge amount of Andrew's Honey, an impractically large amount of hops, and unleashed hell upon our brewing system! The end result is simultaneously dry and fruity, with just the slightest underlying hint of honey; we advise you to grab some while you can, since this beer ain't gonna stick around too long!

Somewhat to our surprise, one of the most common requests* we get is for none other than the humble Amber Ale. This caught us off guard for a bit, as it's hardly the most sexy style, until we realized that we'd been entirely missing the point - not everyone wants intense assault on the tastebuds, as is the case with many of these Xtreme Flavor Blast Beerz. Some people want a beer that's Just A Beer - no more no less - so that's why we made this thing! There's some subtle complexity lurking amongst the flavors if you care to look for it, or you can just drink it and not make a big fuss and that's cool too.

Our take on a classic Oktoberfest staple is made to showcase the toasty breadiness of grains we got from Blue Ox Malthouse, as well as some freshass fruity hoppiness from our friends at Four Star Farms. This malty masterpiece ain't gonna disappoint - Prost!

Teamaker hops aren't commonly used in beer - their alpha acids (which contribute beer's bracing bitterness) are so low compared to other varieties (classic hop varieties typically have an alpha acid content of 5-10%, with newer varieties reaching up to 20%. These clock in at 1%) that they're a bit impractical to brew with (most folks make hop tea with 'em, hence the name). But we thought it sounded like a cool little underdog of a hop, and since we didn't know much about it we dumped a big ol' bag of it into a nice, medium-bodied pale ale! This beer's a delightful, curious little thing - these woody, floral aromas are keepin' us bendin' our elbows every time we pour a pint for "research purposes."
The latest in our single hop series, Summit smells like a picnic and delivers an all-around satisfying drinking experience.
In the honor of a sassy lil' scottie who brightened our lives until late last year, we brewed up a small sweet stout and tossed in some chipotles and black peppercorns to give it a spicy little zip!

While there are some practical reasons why we chose this as our first beer, we care much more about the tasty reasons. We've loaded this with gobs and gobs of the finest hops that Four Star Farms (located in MA!) has to offer, and them hops are braced by solid, bready, slightly sweet backbone provided by Valley Malt (also from MA!).

This is a beer I'd never originally intended to brew more than once, but it ended up being an accidental winner. I had just gotten a bunch of a new hop variety and I wanted to see what it was all about, so I brewed a beer with a really simple recipe so there wouldn't be any other flavors/aromas competing with the hops. And oh man, it was so good. It didn't hurt that I was trying out a cool new hop, but more importantly I'm a big proponent of New Beer Rule #6 - the best beer is the one that was in the empty glass. And considering how fast we went through that pilot batch, I knew it would be silly not to keep using this recipe.

We like a bone-dry saison as much as anybody, but this time around we figured we'd boost the body on this mamma jamma (all the more feels for your mouth) with a fistful of oats 'n rye. Other than that, we went for a fairly straightforward interpretation of the style so we could really let the distinctive character of our house yeast shine through.
We like to keep somethin' malty, dry, and a little roasty kickin' around, so we brewed up this humble brown ale for you!

Part Belgian Strong, part English Barleywine, part glassful of nap, the Beer of Truth will shine its light upon you and reveal what you are truly made of (odds are, it will reveal that you are made of somebody who really wants pizza right now). â

beers.beerDescription: This American-style IPA stands head and shoulders above its hoppy brethren, blending pale and honey malts to balance the palate without interfering in your herbal reverie, and creating a new American classic.

Brewed with Pilsner, CaraVienne, and Rye malts, plus Magnum and Spalter hops.  But the driving force behind this beer is the contribution from whole Black, Green, White, and Pink peppercorns. Added to the brewkettle, these four fab peppercorns harmonize with spicy hops while the malted rye and our Belgian yeast hold down the backbeat.

CBCâs Great Pumpkin Ale is brewed with over 150 pounds of fresh, locally grown, organic sugar pumpkins in each batch, and it has an appropriately distinct orange hue. The subtle fresh pumpkin flavor is enhanced by the addition of a touch of traditional autumn spices, and is guaranteed to please even the most finicky of harvest-time ale fanatics. Come raise a glass in honor of the Great Pumpkin!

Pilsner malt and flaked rice provide sweet cereal grain notes while German and Czech hops add spiciness and a balanced bitterness to the finish. Cold fermented and aged with a German lager yeast, the palate is clean with a snappy finish.

Well balanced, medium-bodied, with a deep amber-red color, this beer's complex palate covers all the bases. A malty caramel sweetness is followed by notes of chocolate and a dry, slightly roasty finish, complemented by a touch of fruity, spicy hops.

You want an IPA, youâve got one, but with a twist! âSpring Trainingâ breezes in like a breath of fresh air, ready to awaken your senses from a long, cold winter. Crafted primarily of New England-grown pale malts, the recipe also incorporates Belgian carapils and wheat malts to contribute to the beerâs complex body and straw-golden color. Ahtanum and Palisades hops, both relative newcomers on the hop varietal scene, were chosen for their essence of wildflowers and freshly-cut grass, evocative of springtime breezes. This is in contrast to the piney, earthy and resiny characteristics of most IPAs. In addition to extensive kettle hopping the beer is dry-hopped with even Ahtanums to satisfy your hop-craving.
Big and bold, our Pale Ale distinguishes itself by its huge, fresh hop aroma and flavor. A combination of Cascade and Centennial hops gives this beer its nectarious flavor.

THE CROWD GOES WILD! A smooth bass line of roasted notes establishes the deep end beneath arpeggios of complex chocolate malt, while power chords of caramelized grain open up to an extended malty jam. Black barley teases treacle character and wades into a velvety sea of oak-derived vanilla and toasted coconut tones. Sustained improvisation of fruitiness modulates to an intense finale, and encores with a rich, espresso-roasted reprise, a capella.

Barley, wheat, rye and oats combine with hops and citrus peel in this new American saison. Created by men and women who have forged their own paths to craft your beer, hereâs a liquid reward for heroic people everywhere who take pride in an honest dayâs work.

With elder flowers and dry hopped with Nelson Sauvin.

The best day of the year comes once every summer when the Brew Crew and friends travel to Westport on Massachusettsâ Atlantic Coast to pick fresh heather flowers. After a long day of toiling in the sun, we hustle home and add them to the kettle to create our world famous Heather Ale.Brewed with imported Scottish floor-malted barley, fresh hand-harvested heather flowers are added to the kettle during the boil along with sweet gale and lavender, with a further addition of fresh heather and yarrow to the conditioning tanks.

Every batch of CBC HefeWeizen is brewed with Massachusetts-grown organic wheat, which has been malted for us by our friends in Hadley, MA at Valley Malt. By the way, Weisse (white) and Weizen (wheat) are two interchangeable terms in regards to naming this style, and the words mit hefe (with yeast) indicate that this is an unfiltered beer.

So enjoy your summer with a cold CBC HefeWeizen, and show your support for sustainable, organic farms and small businesses in Massachusetts!

Cerise CassÃ©e is a complex beer in both process and palate. Multiple fermentations begin in stainless steel with our house ale yeast, then spontaneous refermentation and aging along with 300 pounds of sour cherries takes place in the infamous CBC barrel cellar.

Brewed in the tradition of the fresh, blond ales of Cologne, Germany, our Golden ale is light in body, crisp and very refreshing. Its soft malt flavor is balanced by delicate, spicy hop flavors and finishes.

A smoothbore with a flared muzzle, similar but more refined and accurate than its predecessor the Blunderbuss (ah, thereâs the thematic association, Blunderbuss being our winter barleywineâ¦)

In 1642, the first Dutch Colonists came to Queens (present day Maspeth). But within that first year, they got their asses kicked, then booted out (back to Manhattan Island) by the Mespeatches Native American tribe (origins of the name 'Maspeth'). This beer is a recipe using ingredients that those first Dutch colonists would have had access to in 1642. Barley and Cluster hops were available at the time but often in short supply, so to supplement a recipe, colonial brewers used corn, rye, wheat, oats, buckwheat, and honey in their grain bills. To supplement bittering hops if in short supply, spruce tips would be used. All above ingredies are included in this recipe. The rsult is a balanced, sessiony ale - slightly cloudy (from the wheat), slightly earthy and bitter (from the spruce addition) - with a story to ponder... Sort of the 'b' side version of the story of Thanksgiving. 
Call it a colonial pale, old fashioned ale, a gruit, or whatever category you think fits.

In 2008, shortly before the expansion that would bring their Madison Square Park Shake Shack to the world stage, they came to us and asked if we could create a beer to match their delicious burgers. A job like that would call for a great deal of burger-related research, so we jumped at the opportunity.

reviews.text:
Finally made it to this brewery, I have had a lot of Bronx Brewery American Pale Ales at different event and bars around New York City. It is great to see this destination brewery with my own eyes. Now, this area is an industrial location in the South Bronx.  Driving would be the best way to get here but our group of three decided to take the subway which is very doable with a ten minute walk from the 6 Train stop.

As you approach and enter this large industrial facility, there is tasting room to the left and straight ahead to go into the brewery. If you go through the brewery area, there is a large outdoor space. It's December now so it is definitely off-season for this outdoor location but I was told by the Brooklyn Brewery staff and tour guide, Kate that it is a great space on a summer weekend. They are food trucks and live music. I definitely need to come back and check it out.

They offer free tours of the brewery on the weekend. It was a quiet Sunday afternoon so we had a private tour because we were the only new arrivals at tour time. Kate explained very succinctly and efficiently the brewing process and more about Bronx Brewery. Bronx Brewery stated in 2011 but it only opened this brewery location in 2014 after a few years of renovation woes, thanks Hurricane Sandy.

If you check-in with Yelp, you get $1 off a pint after your tasting. We took advantage of this discount which was much appreciated. We decided to eat before we arrived but there is a good selection of small appetizer types of food such as prosciutto ($10), pretzels ($6) and toketti ($6). The toketti are Sardinian style flatbread chip-type munchies.

For the beer, we tried plenty of brews. We ended up with three different pints. The Rye Pale Ale was our first selection a crisp, golden-orange pale ale with rye and piney hops.  The other two selections were the seasonal brews, Winter and Bogsmash. The Winter Pale Ale is an amber colored pale ale brewed with cinnamon, molasses, cloves and ginger that has a spiced the flavor.  The Bogsmash Pale Ale is a fall brew with cranberries with a subtle tart aftertaste.

A few of my friends have personally recommended this location so I am happy to have made it to this location.
Very low-key, full of hip individuals. Great beer, I had the No Resolutions.
The Bronx Brewery is a great place to relax with friends! Great backyard seating and a relaxed bar area with games. The beer is delicious and the staff is friendly and helpful!

beers.beerDescription: This deep amber American-style pale ale is brewed with 5 different barley malts, generous additions of Cascade and Centennial hops, and a unique strain of yeast. It is dry-hopped, unfiltered, and unpasteurized.

Malted and flaked rye make up nearly a quarter of the grain bill for this Rye Pale Ale, offering it a unique and intense spicy rye flavor and golden-orange hue.  Chinook and Crystal hops lend a gentle bitterness and spicy, piney and herbal character and aroma to this rich, bold rye beer.

This balanced and refreshing pale ale is perfect for summer days in the city.  Brewed with British and American 2-row malts, a unique experimental hop variety and dried lemon peel, it offers a subtle and crisp citrus note.  It is dry-hopped, unfiltered and unpasteurized.

Loads of tropical fruit â guava, passion fruit and ripe mango â on the nose, a clean, light body, leading to a refreshingly tart, red wheat malt finish establish this easy-drinking yet wonderfully hoppy 5.0% ABV session IPA.

Two strains of Trappist yeast, one Belgian ale yeast, and Belgian candi sugar highlight this remarkably intricate, fruity, spicy, and earthy straw-colored Belgian Pale Ale. Belgian Pilsner and Biscuit malts from Beloeil and German Vienna malts from Bamberg provide a clean backdrop for the spicy and lightly herbal Sterling hops. A votre santÃ© from the Bronx.

If you are looking for a beer to satisfy your New Year's resolution, make no mistake -- this isn't it. This brew brings hop aromas & bitterness in a big way -- a variety of hops create a spectrum of aromas ranging from citrus, pine, musky, tropical fruit to lemon grass. With a 7.6% ABV and a heavy hop guarantee this is the ideal beer for those who go No Resolutions. Cheers!

This Black Pale Ale offers a smooth and complex contrast of dark chocolate and roasted malt flavors with bright and tropical guava, mango and pear hop flavors and aromas.  Three different American malts stand up to generous amounts of West Coast El Dorado and Citra hops in an unfiltered and unpasteurized ale.  Embrace the darkness of the winter with this hoppy black ale.

Our banner beer for those who make stuff happen.

Bronx Banner is a Kolsch-inspired ale that is brewed using Belgian pilsner, American wheat malts & classic Bavarian hops.  Itâs brilliantly clear-filtered, soft and perfectly balanced.
An amber colored pale ale brewed with cinnamon, molasses, cloves & ginger that delivers a delightful winter spiced flavor.

Fresh juice pressed from New York State apples makes up a quarter of the fermentables of this crisp and easy-drinking Autumn Pale Ale, lending it a slightly acidic, fruity and tannic finish.  Northern Brewer hops from the west coast are added to the kettle and conditioning tank, contributing a woody and subtle mint character.

beers.beerName: Bronx Spring Pale Ale with Tea
beers.beerDescription: A blend of black and chamomile teas brewed to perfect balance with 2 row barley malts and refreshing lemongrass and pine hop bitterness.

A fall seasonal brewed with cranberries giving this pale ale a subtle tart finish.

Cranberries can only grow in a few parts of the world and lucky for us, NY State happens to be one of them.  We used cranberries from a few of NY's best bogs to add a subtle tartness to this seasonal pale ale.  The hops we use provide woody aromas & bitterness and the malt's sweetness keeps the acidity of the berries in check.  We feel the Bog Smash is the perfect complement for the crisp outdoor weather we love to enjoy in the fall.  Plus, it's super fun to yell "Bog Smash", so hope you enjoy!

Easy drinking IPA with loads of tropical hops & subtle tart finish.
To keep pace in New York City you've got to be able to get things done in a New York minute.  It's a fast-paced, frenzied lifestyle that we love being part of but now and then it's good to pump the brakes a bit and slow it all down.  This Session IPA is perfect for those chill moments when you want to lean back and take it all in. We brew this IPA with two of our favorite hops for some amazing tropical fruit aromas and add red wheat malt to give it a crisp, tart finish.  An easy drinking 4.6% ABV makes this the ideal brew for when it's time to Slow Your Roll.

A rich, full bodied stout that delivers a dark roasted and chocolate taste that would make any coffee drinker smile.

Heaps of small-batch roasted Ethiopian coffee from Uptown Coffee Roasters (our next door neighbor) lead the charge in this rich, creamy coffee milk stout.  The milk sugar we add gives it plenty of sweetness but itâs balanced by floral, earthy and mildly bitter Willamette hops so you wonât have too much sugar in your coffee.  If youâre looking for something sweet and chocolatey to warm you up on a cold NYC winter night look no further.

Big floral and tropical aromas set up this delightfully balanced white IPA.

Soft yet slightly tart wheat and lightly toasted malts are complemented by the gentle bitterness of the hops.  Our brewers use late hop additions and dry hopping in the brewing process to give this IPA its big hop nose without an overwhelmingly bitter taste.  This brew is love at first smell.  Cheers!
Double IPA, brewed with tangerine purÃ©e

A spicy Rye IPA thatâs balanced with a generous amount of West Coast hops, giving this brew a strong, pleasant bitterness and raising it to Imperial status with an 8.1% ABV. Our devotion to our Rye Ale runs deep.  After all, it was the second beer we ever brewed.  But we couldnât resist the temptation to make a bigger, more badass version and this spicy Rye IPA delivers.  With heavy citrus aromas on thenose and a crisp, dry, warm finish on the mouth, itâs a complex, yet finely balanced big hoppy beer with an 8.1% ABV that we canât get enough of.  Looks like we committed some infidelity with our Rye Fidelity.

We figured we'd kick off our Bronx Barrel Reserve series with a bang, by short aging our White IPA in NY State red wine barells. The mix of different wine varietals lends notes to strawberries, raspberries, and plums to our already massively juicy IPA.  While resting in these wine barrels we add a dry hop of Pacific Gem and Citra to help set this beer off like a firework for your senses.
A big, fun Red IPA that brings all the spice & heat without the burn!

A refreshingly spicy farmhouse style saison right in time for the summer.

The origins of saison were grounded in the use of this brew by many farmers in Belgium and France as a form of payment (and sustenance) to their farmhands during the hot summer months.  While we here at The Bronx Brewery prefer modern forms of currency, our Brewmaster thought this would be a nice little bonus for the summer.  A complex, yet refreshingly easy to drink beer.  We added 60 pounds of orange blossom honey into the kettle to give this farmhouse ale a delightful citric & sweet aroma.  The malts deliver an earthy and malty biscuit sweetness and the Austrian and Czech hops balance it all with spicy, herbal flavor and aromatic.

A crisp & easy drinking pale ale brewed with freshly pressed apple juice.

This pale ale is made using freshly pressed juice from apples from Soons Orchard in upstate New York.  The apples provide a dry and slight fruity taste balanced by Northern Brewer hops for a subtle wood and mint character.  We feel this is an ideal beer to enjoy when the season changes from T-shirts to sweaters

beers.beerName: Red Zinfandel Aged American Pale Ale
beers.beerDescription: This deep amber, American-style pale ale is brewed with five different barley malts, generous additions of Cascade and Centennial hops, and a unique strain of yeast. It is dry-hopped, unfiltered and unpasteurized. Finally it is aged in a French Oak Old Vine Zinfandel barrel from the Brooklyn Winery to impart rich dark fruit notes and complex Brettanomyces character.

Our brewers gave up their dreams to be rap superstars to pursue the softer lights of the craft beer scene long ago. This Dinkelweizen is their way to payout to those who get after their dreams no matter what they might be.   This brew is made with all NY grown ingredients including spelt malt which gives it an extra nutty taste.  American hefeweizen yeast imparts classic wheat beer characteristics and dry hopping will deliver a heavy dose of hops on the nose.  Thereâs no doubt this beer is a hit.

beers.beerDescription: The hop profile of Flagship APA includes an upfront bitterness complemented with citrus and pine-like aromas followed by a small burst of tropical fruit. Malted barley provides a deep auburn color and a sweet, biscuit-like backbone helping the flavor balance nicely with the bitterness from the hops. The mouthfeel is medium bodied with a hoppy and crisp finish.

Flagship American Wit is a refreshing, light bodied wheat beer. Prized hops from Americaâs northwest region give this ale a citrusy flavor blended with the subtle undertones of our hand ground spices. A balancing malt profile contributes a recognizable golden color in addition to a slight haze from the yeast.

Flagship Breweryâs âMetropolitan Lagerâ is a golden lager that features toasted Vienna and Rye malts. The Rye adds a smooth mouthfeel while floral noble hops are used in abundance for flavor and aroma. This lager is smooth, clean, crisp and exceptionally balanced.

A showcase of some of Flagshipâs favorite hop varieties and executed by using them in abundance. Each hop in IPA lends a unique flavor that when blended produces bursting fruit flavors from citrusy grapefruit to tropical mango in harmony with an ever so slight roast character from the golden malted barley. Designed for full hop flavor experience without overpowering bitterness.

A malty brew that uses Vienna and Munich varieties of malted barley that are complemented with German malted rye and German chocolate rye. Bavarian noble hops balance the beer with a mild bitterness and soft floral aroma. The result is a full-bodied dark copper colored ale with a smooth texture and spicy-like characteristic from the rye malt.

Flagship Dark Mild is black in color due to a complex malt profile thatâs packed with flavor by using a wide variety of roasted, toasted, and caramel malts. The mildness comes from a soft hop character and lower alcohol content making this light bodied ale a sessionable salute to our fondness for dark beer.

A foundation consisting of American wheat and Golden Promise malts give this beer light sweetness and a slight haze. The all-star of this ale is a hop called âSummer.â This spawn of the noble hop, Saaz, is subtle and used in abundance contributing slight aromas of hop spice, earthiness, and tropical melon. American ale yeast helps to provide a crispness that is dry but balanced. Deep yellow color and a light body make this summer beer approachable and sessionable.

As we approach the inevitable winter, Flagship introduces âWee Heavy.â  Brewed in the style of strong Scottish ales, a longer boil adds âcaramelizationâ to the brewing process and helps produce a full body and higher alcohol content in addition to malty sweetness. We Americanize this dark brown colored beer by using a copious amount of pacific northwest hops.

The British Mild is a session ale known for soft hop character and lower alcohol content. Flagship VAN DAM is black in color due to a complex malt profile. Using a wide variety of roasted, toasted, and caramel malts, this ale is bursting with dark beer character. The addition of Madagascar Bourbon vanilla blends a pleasant richness to the existing flavors. A medium but mellow body gives VAN DAM enjoyable drinkability during the winter months.

The pairing of Stout with oysters has been enjoyed for centuries and Flagship Oyster Stout combines the two into one delicious apÃ©ritif. Roasted barley united with chocolate rye, midnight wheat, and flaked oats gives this brew dark color and roasty flavor while providing a smooth mouthfeel and rich body. The flavor blends nicely with a mineral brininess from Long Island harvested oysters that are boiled in the brewing process, shell and all. Designed to be enjoyed with oysters raw or cooked, but approachable and encouraged to be enjoyed all occasions.
